default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default3 default              defaultWhat are the solutions defaultto address the barriers that defaultpoor defaultdisabled people face when accessing WASH services? defaultImproving accessibilitydefault&#xa0;default3.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe most cost-effective way to improve accessibility for disabled people is to 
defaultinvolve 
defaultthem
default in the design 
defaultprocess 
defaultand 
defaultincorporate inclusive 
defaulttechnology
default 
defaultfrom the outset, rather than making expensive changes later. WEDC research shows that the additional cost of making a 
defaultnew 
defaultschool latrine accessible is less than 3% of the overall cost of the latrine
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWaterAid and WEDC are 
defaultdeveloping low tech, 
defaultlow cost inclusive WASH adaptations and designs for the household and public places (eg schools, market places, health centres) to ensure people with disabilities are able to access them. These include safe and secure toilets with ramps, wider entrances, r
defaultoom inside to allow a wheelchair user and a carer to enter and turn with ease, simple handrails, and movable wooden toilet seats that can be placed over pit latrines. Simple adaptations to water points include clearing the path to the water apron, putting 
defaultin ramps, allowing room for a wheelchair user to turn easily, incorporating a water container resting stand, and fitting a t-handle bar to the handpump.
default&#xa0;
default3.3.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultInstalling rainwater harvesting jars near disabled 
defaultpeople’s homes
default can reduce reliance on others to col
defaultlect water from handpumps that are far away. The rainwater can be used for washing, supplement
defaulting 
defaultdrinking water collected from 
defaultprotected 
defaultwells. 
